# --- ssh-agent persistence (Linux / VPS) --------------------------------------
# keychain reuses a single ssh-agent across logins so you unlock a key once.
# macOS does NOT need this: launchd runs a persistent agent and Keychain stores
# the passphrase — set `AddKeysToAgent yes` + `UseKeychain yes` in ~/.ssh/config
# and `ssh-add --apple-use-keychain` once instead.
# The guard skips keychain's ~110ms scan when a working agent is already inherited
# (e.g. a tmux pane), so it only pays the cost bootstrapping the first agent.
# if [[ -z "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" || ! -S "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" ]] && command -v keychain >/dev/null 2>&1; then
#   eval "$(keychain --eval --quiet --agents ssh id_ed25519)"
# fi

# --- Secrets (1Password CLI) --------------------------------------------------
# Secrets live in 1Password and are fetched at runtime by `op`. The tracked
# zsh/op.zsh shim authenticates `op` the SAME way on every machine (macOS + VPS):
# a SERVICE-ACCOUNT TOKEN — no desktop-app / biometric integration.
#
#   One-time setup per machine:
#     1. 1Password web → Developer → Service Accounts → create one, scoped to
#        ONLY the vault(s) this machine needs. Copy the ops_… token (shown once).
#     2. Write it to a 0600 file WITHOUT it hitting history or `ps`:
#          ( umask 077
#            install -d -m 700 "${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-$HOME/.config}/op"
#            IFS= read -rs 'tok?service-account token: '
#            print -r -- "$tok" > "${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-$HOME/.config}/op/service-account-token"
#            unset tok )
#     3. Verify: `op whoami` and `op vault ls`.
#     Rotate/revoke the token in 1Password anytime; nothing else changes.
#
# Consuming secrets — never export them at shell init:
#   • Launch a tool with secrets injected only into ITS process, from a
#     committable references file (op:// refs, no values):
#         # agents.refs.env  (safe to commit — references, not secrets)
#         ANY_SERVICE_API_KEY=op://Private/AnyService/credential
#         op run --env-file=agents.refs.env -- <dispatcher-command>
#   • Or pull one secret on demand into the current shell (use sparingly):
#         openv GITHUB_TOKEN op://Private/GitHub/token
